    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-03-19T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-03-19T14:00:00-05:00" n="91"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d91">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">641.006/547: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-03-19T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 19, 1940—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 19—3 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>692. Department’s 512, March 18 and Embassy’s 682, March 18, 7 p.m.<note n="48"
                        xml:id="d91fn48">Latter not printed.</note> Further energetic
                    representations have been made in appropriate quarters today, and it is believed
                    that they gained some appreciation of the unfavorable reception recent British
                    import orders have had in the United States. Board of Trade advises tonight that
                    supplementary statement has been prepared for release by Embassy in Washington
                    which they expect to cable immediately.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
